<ul>
  <li>When we speak, we are generally expressing two messages at once: a literal message and a meta-message, which is a sort of commentary on the whatever it is weâ€™re literally saying. Meta-messages mean things like, â€œI know Iâ€™m teasing you, but itâ€™s out of affection,â€ â€œIâ€™m sarcastically telling you youâ€™re stupid,â€ â€œIâ€™m not sure about this, so please cut me some slack,â€ â€œMy words arenâ€™t all that important, but my point is that I like you and am enjoying spending time with you.â€ While we often use body language and inflection to convey meta-messages, we sometimes do it with words, too.</li>
